LAGOS  – Agege Local Government Area in Lagos State has initiated programmes and policies to make the business environment friendly to businessmen, women, and micro, small and medium enterprises in the area. Speaking at the just concluded Agege Trade Fair in Agege, Mr. Michael Abiola, the executive vice chairman of the election, said that the local government collaborated with Verified Creative House, a marketing and branding company, to organise the fair in order to promote enterprise, entrepreneurship and startups in the local government. He said that small businesses play a critical role in the economic life of the people at the grassroots level, adding that this was the reason is doing everything possible to encourage small businesses to thrive. Abiola disclosed that the local government paid for small businesses to participate at the trade fair. “We brought people who might ordinarily not afford to pay for stalls and not make enough sales in their shops and other places. We want them to make bigger sales and build networks and showcase their products to a larger audience and make greater profit in the process. “We know that things are difficult for people at the grassroots in the country and that is why we thought it wise for pay for spaces for small businesses to participate at the fair,” he stated. The Agege Local Government chairman added that the idea was to give small business owners a sense of belonging and enable them make more profit.